@jasonhurdlow6607   Oh really, that's interesting.

Historically the "New 70" would rival the "Old 80Ti" even going back to the 2011 / 28nm cards. It seems like the 50 series is Nvidia's lowest point for consumers. I would rank it as such: RTX-50, RTX-20, RTX-40, GTX-7, RTX-30, GTX-10, GTX-6, GTX-9.

Thank goodness for channels like Hardware Unboxed for doing the work, and spreading the truth.

 @zWORMzGaming  love you bro
i watch you
since 2020

 @zealgaming8161  Pricing from years ago doesn't equate to a product "aging well." The entire 30 series sold out throughout the pandemic years and was being scalped due to Covid and more demand than supply. 

In reality, the 3090 didn't age well at all. The 3080 TI rendered it pointless to buy one unless you needed the extra 8 GB of VRAM and 1-5% more performance, and the 4090 absolutely stomped the 3090 in performance. 

It's hilarious how many people are still trying to sell their 3090s on Facebook for $800+.

 @kevinerbs2778  Mostly because it is added value. DLSS is way better than FSR 3.1 (we dont know about 4), more widely available. Nvidias drivers, at least in the past have proven to have less issues overall. Cuda is important to those who need it etc.  RT performance is also better. 

AMD also has its own value proposition: Linux drivers - if you are building a linux PC, you're better off buying amd.

In the end you are making the decision for yourself, but to say that nvidia does not have more advantages than amd when it comes to their cards would be dishonest.

 @bonitaritz7052  I've had my new PC for a few days so far, I've tried Star Wars Outlaws, it runs nicely even on a 4K monitor, but it's not without compromise. I used the recommended settings by Nvidia app which optimizes the game and the game looks good and FPS is mostly above 100. 
It really depends a lot on how one plays with the settings, but otherwise for the price I'd say it's a good graphics card. 
I'm satisfied.

 @fenneckw  
If you mainly play your kernel level anti cheat gooner games than yeah Linux won't work for you.
Majority of games on Steam run perfectly fine though.
